-- Regression: emit_c.c RC_ALLOC malloc without NULL check (FIX-01 rank 4).
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 65 CORRECTNESS-AUDIT.md §3 row 4 and §6 row
-- 2 flagged src/lir/emit_c.c:3179-3192 (the IRON_LIR_RC_ALLOC codegen case)
-- as the same pattern as rank 3 but for the `rc` keyword's reference-counted
-- allocation path. Every Iron program that used `rc` had ironc emit a bare
-- `T *_vN = malloc(sizeof(T)); *_vN = val;` sequence with zero NULL check,
-- so every `rc`-using binary was one OOM away from silent SIGSEGV. The
-- blast radius mirrors rank 3 — it covers every reference-counted object
-- construction the compiler emits.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.** Pre-fix (emit_c.c:3179 case body):
--     %s *_vN = (%s *)malloc(sizeof(%s));    <- line 3192
--     *_vN    = inner_val;                    <- line 3198, may deref NULL
--
-- Post-fix:
--     %s *_vN = (%s *)malloc(sizeof(%s));
--     if (!_vN) iron_oom_abort("emit_c RC_ALLOC");
--     *_vN    = inner_val;
--
-- Identical guard pattern to rank 3 except for the stderr location literal
-- ("emit_c RC_ALLOC" vs "emit_c HEAP_ALLOC"), so a stderr grep after any
-- OOM abort can immediately distinguish which allocation path failed.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** src/lir/emit_c.c IRON_LIR_RC_ALLOC case rewritten to
-- emit a 3-line `if (!_vN) iron_oom_abort(...);` guard between the malloc
-- call and the `*_vN =` dereference. Covers FIX-01 rank 4 from the Phase 65
-- audit. Phase 67-02 Task 3. This fixture verifies the guard is present in
-- the generated C and that a normal non-OOM `rc Config(5, 3000)` still
-- compiles and runs correctly.
--
-- **Severity.** H — same blast radius as rank 3 but scoped to `rc`-using
-- programs; pre-fix silent SIGSEGV on OOM, post-fix bisectable stderr
-- diagnostic naming the exact allocation arm.

object Config {
  var max_retries: Int
  var timeout_ms: Int
}

func main() {
  val cfg = rc Config(5, 3000)
  println("retries: {cfg.max_retries}")
  println("timeout: {cfg.timeout_ms}")
}
